Lab 05 – Brain-Inspired Learning Models
Course: ITAI 4374 – Neuroscience as a Model for AI
Student: Orhan Gumus
Semester: Spring 2026

What I Did
This lab investigated learning models that draw more directly from biological principles, moving beyond standard backpropagation toward approaches inspired by synaptic plasticity, competitive learning, and self-organization.
Key activities included:

Implementing Hebbian and anti-Hebbian learning rules
Exploring unsupervised learning methods inspired by cortical self-organization
Studying synaptic plasticity mechanisms including Long-Term Potentiation (LTP) and Long-Term Depression (LTD)
Building and visualizing self-organizing maps (SOMs) as models of cortical topographic mapping


What I Learned
This lab deepened my appreciation for how much of modern machine learning is still catching up to the sophistication of biological learning. Synaptic plasticity is not a single mechanism but a family of processes that operate at different timescales and in response to different signals.
Self-organizing maps were particularly fascinating — watching the network spontaneously develop topographic structure mirroring how the brain organizes sensory representations was a powerful demonstration of emergent order.

Challenges I Faced

Implementing competitive learning required careful normalization to prevent "dead neurons" — units that never win competition and stop learning.
Understanding the difference between short-term and long-term plasticity, and when each applies, took multiple readings of the material.
Visualizing high-dimensional SOM outputs in a meaningful way required creative use of dimensionality reduction techniques.
